  <chunk id="25e53f84ee9bb3d0f9be47a740938c12dbbd559b.c2" text="Methodology/Principal Findings: CCHF virus-infected IFNAR 2/2 mice died 2-6 days post infection with elevated aminotransferase levels and high virus titers in blood and organs. Main pathological alteration was acute hepatitis with extensive bridging necrosis, reactive hepatocyte proliferation, and mild to moderate inflammatory response with monocyte/macrophage activation. Virus-infected and apoptotic hepatocytes clustered in the necrotic areas. Ribavirin, arbidol, and T-705 suppressed virus replication in vitro by $3 log units (IC 50 0.6-2.8 mg/ml; IC 90 1.2-4.7 mg/ml). Ribavirin [100 mg/(kg6d)] did not increase the survival rate of IFNAR 2/2 mice, but prolonged the time to death (p,0.001) and reduced the aminotransferase levels and the virus titers. Arbidol [150 mg/(kg6d)] had no efficacy in vivo. Animals treated with T-705 at 1 h [15, 30, and 300 mg/(kg6d)] or up to 2 days [300 mg/(kg6d)] post infection survived, showed no signs of disease, and had no virus in blood and organs. Co-administration of ribavirin and T-705 yielded beneficial rather than adverse effects.">
